<h3><a id="concepts" name="concepts"></a>1. Concepts</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>
This project is designed to
have you query a MySQL database with PHP and to use one of the
PEAR packages. You will learn these concepts:
</p>
<ul>
<li>Do a multi-table query from the MySQL database
</li>
<li>Fetch the query result set row by row using a loop
</li>
<li>Process the column values of each row
</li>
<li>Use an HTML form to get
user input for the WHERE clause of the query
</li>
<li>Use the PEAR DB package to
make your query generic for use against any DBMS
</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>

<h3><a id="readings" name="readings"></a>2.
Readings</h3>

<blockquote>
<p>To prepare for this project
you should study or review the following:</p>

<p><a id="readings" name="readings"><strong>PHP and MySQL Web Development, 3rd
Edition.</strong> Luke Welling
&amp; Laura Thomson, Sams</a></p>
<ul>
<li>Chapter 8, Designing a Web Database
</li>
<li>Chapter 9, Creating a Web Database
</li>
<li>Chapter 10, Working with a MySQL Database
</li>
<li>Chapter 11, Accessing a MySQL Database from the Web with PHP
</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>

<h3><a id="overview" name="overview"></a>3.
Project Overview</h3>

<blockquote>
<p>This project will introduce you to web database application development
using PHP and MySQL, and the PEAR repository.</p>
</blockquote>

<h3><a id="execs" name="execs"></a>4.
Exercises</h3>

<blockquote>
<a id="ex1" name="ex1"></a>Create a directory named 
<b>project3</b> under your web server's document root directory on your hard drive.
Place all HTML files and PHP scripts for this project in this new directory. <br />
<br />
<b>Note:</b> If you are working on an MATC lab computer, always save a copy of
this directory and all the files in it to either the class server, a USB
thumb drive, a floppy disk or similar media, at the end of each work
session. Otherwise your work will be lost!
  
<h4>Exercise 1</h4>
<blockquote>
<p>Download two files: an include file and a PHP query,
into your project3 directory and
add an HTML form to input a Winery name from the user.</p>
<ol>
<li><span style="font-weight: bold;"></span>Download
the <a href="p3db.inc.php.txt">p3db.inc.php</a> include file and the
<a href="p3select.php.txt">p3select.php</a> file containing a MySQL
query from the Blackboard version of this document.
</li>
<li>Modify the <b>p3db.inc.php</b> file to contain your MySQL
username and password. Then run the <b>p3select.php</b>
script to verify that it displays the list of wines offered by one Winery.
</li>
<li>Add an HTML form to get the Winery name from the user. The
HTML form can either be added to the file containing the PHP code or
created in a separate file named <b>winery.html</b>, your choice!
</li>
<li>Modify the code in <b>p3select.php</b>
so that the user-entered Winery name is used by the SQL query instead
of the hard-coded value provided.
</li>
<li>Save your revised PHP code to a file named <b>p3ex1.php</b>.
</li>
</ol>
<p>If you created a winery.html file for your HTML form, be sure
to include it in the Zip or Tar archive you submit.
</p>
</blockquote>

<h4>Exercise 2</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Modify the PHP code from Exercise 1 to use the PEAR DB package
to access the MySQL database:
</p>
<ul>
<li>See Listing 11.5 on page 280-2 of the text.</li>
<li>Note: PEAR may not be properly installed during some PHP5 installations,
so you may need to follow procedures discussed in class to verify your computer's
PEAR installation and to ensure that it includes the PEAR DB package.
</li>
<li>You will need to use the directive:
<code>require_once('DB.php');</code>
</li>
<li>On some computers you may need to use the full path:
<code>require_once('/usr/lib/php/DB.php');</code>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Save your revised PHP code to a file named <b>p3ex2.php</b>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>

